A civil society group, Equity and Transparency Development Initiative has petitioned the Independent Corrupt Practices and Other Related Matters Commission (ICPC) over alleged financial infractions by two officials of the Nigerian Bulk Electricity Trade Company Plc (NBET). In the petition signed by the group’s national coordinator, Mr. Ijewa Zeb Obioma and addressed to the chairman, ICPC alleged that the officials flagrantly abused their office. The group, therefore, wants the commission to investigate and prosecute the officials whom it claimed used their official position to secure a contract for a company which they had interest thereby enriching themselves against the code of conduct for public servants. The petition reads: “We are a registered non-governmental organisation with the Corporate Affairs Commission (CAC) geared towards fighting for equity, social justice and financial transparency both in the public and private sectors of the country, for the betterment of Nigeria and Nigerians. “As part of our cardinal objectives, we abhor official impunity and illegal self-enrichment to the detriment of country’s collective progress and enthronement of everlasting corrupt-free society, “Our belief and subsequent stand on the fight against corruption being spearheaded by President Muhammadu Buhari, as exemplified by the vigorous ways your agency has been on the forefront to see that the president’s efforts to totally eliminate this ugly menace, is highly commendable and need all the necessary cooperation from the citizenry of which our NGO, has not relented in boldly identifying with this noble crusade. “It’s therefore on this premise that we want to bring to your notice the activities of two management staff members of Nigeria Bulk Electricity Trading Plc otherwise known as NBET, whose stock in trade, according to information available to us, is manipulating records of the agency to perpetuate corruption, presenting and altering curriculum vitae (CV) to gain employment/promotions, favouritism, nepotism and using the proceeds of corruption to erect multi-million mansions; far ahead of their official emoluments” When contacted, the two officers denied any involvement of any financial infractions in their organisation, accusing the petitioners of mischief.